oks:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">.schema tablename</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Print the entire table:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">SELECT * FROM tablename;</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">List all of the available SQLite prompt commands:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">.help</span></blockquote>','use ADB in Android Studio to view an SQLite DB','','inherit','closed','closed','','167-revision-v1','','','2016-10-17 19:35:30','2016-10-17 23:35:30','',167,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/167-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(175,1,'2016-10-17 19:35:38','2016-10-17 23:35:38','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Find all info here:http://developer.android.com/tools/help/sqlite3.html</span>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">How to find your android sdk path</span></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Open Android studio Goto Android Studio&gt;Preference Search for sdk.</span>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">running the sqlite from adb</span></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"> 1- Go to your platform-tools folder in a command prompt</span>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"> 2- Enter the commandadb devicesto get the list of your devices</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ cd/Users/zhexiao/Library/Android/sdk/platform-tools</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ ./adb devices</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3- Connect a shell to your device:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$./adb -s emulator-5554 shell</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4- Navigate to the folder containing your db file:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ cddata/data/&lt;your-package-name&gt;/databases/</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">5- list all file:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ ls -al</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">6- run sqlite3 to connect to your db:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">sqlite3&lt;your-db-name&gt;.db</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">7- run sqlite3 commands that you like eg:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Select*fromtable1where...;</span></blockquote>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">SQLite cheatsheet</span></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">List the tables in your database:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">.tables</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">List how the table looks:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">.schema tablename</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Print the entire table:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">SELECT * FROM tablename;</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">List all of the available SQLite prompt commands:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">.help</span></blockquote>','use ADB in Android Studio to view an SQLite DB','','inherit','closed','closed','','167-revision-v1','','','2016-10-17 19:35:38','2016-10-17 23:35:38','',167,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/167-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(177,1,'2016-10-17 19:37:28','2016-10-17 23:37:28','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Find all info here:http://developer.android.com/tools/help/sqlite3.html</span>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">How to find your android sdk path</span></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Open Android studio Goto Android Studio&gt;Preference Search for sdk.</span>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Running the sqlite from adb</span></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"> 1- Go to your platform-tools folder in a command prompt</span>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"> 2- Enter the commandadb devicesto get the list of your devices</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ cd/Users/zhexiao/Library/Android/sdk/platform-tools</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ ./adb devices</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3- Connect a shell to your device:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$./adb -s emulator-5554 shell</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4- Navigate to the folder containing your db file:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ cddata/data/&lt;your-package-name&gt;/databases/</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">5- list all file:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ ls -al</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">6- run sqlite3 to connect to your db:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">sqlite3&lt;your-db-name&gt;.db</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">7- run sqlite3 commands that you like eg:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Select*fromtable1where...;</span></blockquote>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">SQLite cheatsheet</span></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">List the tables in your database:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">.tables</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">List how the table looks:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">.schema tablename</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Print the entire table:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">SELECT * FROM tablename;</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">List all of the available SQLite prompt commands:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">.help</span></blockquote>','use ADB in Android Studio to view an SQLite DB','','inherit','closed','closed','','167-revision-v1','','','2016-10-17 19:37:28','2016-10-17 23:37:28','',167,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/167-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(178,1,'2016-10-17 19:43:34','2016-10-17 23:43:34','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Find all info here:http://developer.android.com/tools/help/sqlite3.html</span>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">How to find your android sdk path</span></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Open Android studio Goto Android Studio&gt;Preference Search for sdk.</span>\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Running the sqlite from adb</span></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"> 1- Go to your platform-tools folder in a command prompt</span>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"> 2- Enter the commandadb devicesto get the list of your devices</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ cd/Users/zhexiao/Library/Android/sdk/platform-tools</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ ./adb devices</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3- Connect a shell to your device:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$./adb -s emulator-5554 shell</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4- Navigate to the folder containing your db file:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ cddata/data/&lt;your-package-name&gt;/databases/</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">5- list all file:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ ls -al</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">6- run sqlite3 to connect to your db:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">sqlite3&lt;your-db-name&gt;</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">7- run sqlite3 commands that you like eg:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Select*fromtable1where...;</span></blockquote>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">SQLite cheatsheet</span></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">List the tables in your database:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">.tables</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">List how the table looks:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">.schema tablename</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Print the entire table:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">SELECT * FROM tablename;</span></blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">List all of the available SQLite prompt commands:</span>\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">.help</span></blockquote>','use ADB in Android Studio to view an SQLite DB','','inherit','closed','closed','','167-revision-v1','','','2016-10-17 19:43:34','2016-10-17 23:43:34','',167,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/167-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(179,1,'2016-10-21 11:21:54','2016-10-21 15:21:54','1.Update your system and install latest npm\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo apt-get install npm</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">2. Install Grunt</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$ sudonpm install -g grunt-init</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$grunt-init gruntfile</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">4.Installing Grunt and gruntplugins</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$ npm install grunt --save-dev</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$npm install grunt-contrib-jshint --save-dev</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The easiest way to add Grunt and gruntplugins to an existing package.json is with the command npm install &lt;module&gt; --save-dev. Not only will this install &lt;module&gt; locally, but it will automatically be added to the devDependencies section, using a tilde version range.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">5.The Gruntfile</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The Gruntfile.js or Gruntfile.coffee file is a valid JavaScript or CoffeeScript file that belongs in the root directory of your project, next to the package.json file, and should be committed with your project source.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">6.Running Grunt</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">You can find your project plugin in here:http://gruntjs.com/plugins, if you open your Gruntfile.js, you seea task like this:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote><strong>grunt.registerTask(\'default\', [\'jshint\', \'concat\', \'sass\']);</strong></blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Then you can running your project by:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$ grunt default --force</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">7.File change and auto running task</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Add <strong>watch</strong>in the config file:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n\r\n ...\r\n\r\n watch : {\r\n   sass_file:{\r\n     // any file under the sass folder changes\r\n     files : [\'../sass/*.scss\'],\r\n     // running the sass task\r\n     tasks: [\'sass\']\r\n   }\r\n },\r\n sass : {\r\n   dist : {\r\n     options : {\r\n       style : \'expanded\',\r\n       sourcemap : \'auto\',\r\n       noCache : true\r\n     },\r\n    files : {\r\n       \'../css/index.css\' : \'../sass/index.scss\'\r\n     }\r\n   }\r\n }\r\n ...\r\n\r\n})</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The above watch meaning when any file changes under the sass folder, running the task <strong>sass</strong>, so we have to define a <strong>sass task. </strong>After that, we should register the watch command use the following code.</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><strong>grunt.registerTask(\'watch-default\', [\'watch\']);</strong></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nThen you can running your project by:\r\n<blockquote>$ grunt watch-default--force</blockquote>\r\n<h1 class=\"p1\">Grunt Configuration</h1>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">1.Task Configuration and Targets</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">When a task is run, Grunt looks for its configuration under a property of the same name. Multi-tasks can have multiple configurations, defined using arbitrarily named \"targets.\" In the example below, the concat task has foo and bar targets, while the uglify task only has a bar target.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n // concat task \"foo\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n // concat task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n uglify: {\r\n bar: {\r\n // uglify task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">2.Options</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Inside a task configuration, an options property may be specified to override built-in defaults.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">3.Compact Format</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">This form allows a single src-dest (source-destination) file mapping per-target. It is most commonly used for read-only tasks, like grunt-contrib-jshint, where a single src property is needed, and no dest key is relevant. This format also supports additional properties per src-dest file mapping.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n jshint: {\r\n foo: {\r\n src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\']\r\n },\r\n },\r\n concat: {\r\n bar: {\r\n src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n dest: \'dest/b.js\',\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Files Object Format</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">This form supports multiple src-dest mappings per-target, where the property name is the destination file, and its value is the source file(s). Any number of src-dest file mappings may be specified in this way, but additional properties may not be specified per mapping.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/a.js\': [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'],\r\n \'dest/a1.js\': [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/b.js\': [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n \'dest/b1.js\': [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Files Array Format</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">This form supports multiple src-dest file mappings per-target, while also allowing additional properties per mapping.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'], dest: \'dest/a.js\'},\r\n {src: [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'], dest: \'dest/a1.js\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'], dest: \'dest/b/\', nonull: true},\r\n {src: [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'], dest: \'dest/b1/\', filter: \'isFile\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">4.Globbing patterns</p>\r\nIt is often impractical to specify all source filepaths individually, so Grunt supports filename expansion (also known as globbing) via the built-in node-glob and minimatch libraries.\r\n\r\nWhile this isn\'t a comprehensive tutorial on globbing patterns, know that in a filepath:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>* matches any number of characters, but not /</li>\r\n 	<li>? matches a single character, but not /</li>\r\n 	<li>** matches any number of characters, including /, as long as it\'s the only thing in a path part</li>\r\n 	<li>{} allows for a comma-separated list of \"or\" expressions</li>\r\n 	<li>! at the beginning of a pattern will negate the match</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAll most people need to know is that foo/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory, but foo/**/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory and all of its subdirectories.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Working with Grunt','','publish','open','open','','working-with-grunt','','','2017-01-17 17:11:49','2017-01-17 22:11:49','',0,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/?p=179',0,'post','',0),(180,1,'2016-10-20 19:51:08','2016-10-20 23:51:08','1.Update your system and install latest npm\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo apt-get install npm</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">2. Install Grunt</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"></p>','Install Grunt and manage your javascript lib','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-v1','','','2016-10-20 19:51:08','2016-10-20 23:51:08','',179,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/179-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(181,1,'2016-10-21 10:41:24','2016-10-21 14:41:24','1.Update your system and install latest npm\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo apt-get install npm</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">2. Install Grunt</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"></p>','Install Grunt and manage your javascript lib','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-v1','','','2016-10-21 10:41:24','2016-10-21 14:41:24','',179,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/179-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(182,1,'2016-10-21 11:21:54','2016-10-21 15:21:54','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Update your system and install latest npm</span>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\" style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install npm</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2. Install Grunt</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudonpm install -g grunt-init</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$grunt-init gruntfile</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Installing Grunt and gruntplugins</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ npm install grunt --save-dev</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$npm install grunt-contrib-jshint --save-dev</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The easiest way to add Grunt and gruntplugins to an existing package.json is with the command npm install &lt;module&gt; --save-dev. Not only will this install &lt;module&gt; locally, but it will automatically be added to the devDependencies section, using a tilde version range.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">5.The Gruntfile</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The Gruntfile.js or Gruntfile.coffee file is a valid JavaScript or CoffeeScript file that belongs in the root directory of your project, next to the package.json file, and should be committed with your project source.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"></p>','Install Grunt','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-v1','','','2016-10-21 11:21:54','2016-10-21 15:21:54','',179,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/179-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(183,1,'2016-10-21 16:40:46','2016-10-21 20:40:46','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Update your system and install latest npm</span>\n<blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\" style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install npm</span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2. Install Grunt</span></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudonpm install -g grunt-init</span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</span></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$grunt-init gruntfile</span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Installing Grunt and gruntplugins</span></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ npm install grunt --save-dev</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$npm install grunt-contrib-jshint --save-dev</span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The easiest way to add Grunt and gruntplugins to an existing package.json is with the command npm install &lt;module&gt; --save-dev. Not only will this install &lt;module&gt; locally, but it will automatically be added to the devDependencies section, using a tilde version range.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">5.The Gruntfile</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The Gruntfile.js or Gruntfile.coffee file is a valid JavaScript or CoffeeScript file that belongs in the root directory of your project, next to the package.json file, and should be committed with your project source.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">6.Running Grunt</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">You can find your project plugin in here:http://gruntjs.com/plugins, if you open your Gruntfile.js, you seea task like this:</span></p>\n\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>grunt.registerTask(\'default\', [\'jshint\', \'concat\', \'sass\']);</strong></span></blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Then you can running your project by:</span></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ grunt default --force</span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">7.File change and auto running task</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">Add <strong>watch</strong>in the config file:</p>\n\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\n\n ...\n\n watch : {\n   sass_file:{\n     // any file under the sass folder changes\n     files : [\'../sass/*.scss\'],\n     // running the sass task\n     tasks: [\'sass\']\n   }\n },\n sass : {\n   dist : {\n     options : {\n       style : \'expanded\',\n       sourcemap : \'auto\',\n       noCache : true\n     },\n    files : {\n       \'../css/index.css\' : \'../sass/index.scss\'\n     }\n   }\n }\n ...\n\n})</pre>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The above watch meaning when any file changes under the sass folder, running the task <strong>sass</strong>, so we have to define a <strong>sass task. </strong>After that, we should register the watch command.</span></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>grunt.registerTask(\'watch-default\', [\'watch\']);</strong></span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<h1 class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Grunt Configuration</span></h1>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Task Configuration and Targets</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">When a task is run, Grunt looks for its configuration under a property of the same name. Multi-tasks can have multiple configurations, defined using arbitrarily named \"targets.\" In the example below, the concat task has foo and bar targets, while the uglify task only has a bar target.</span></p>\n\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\n concat: {\n foo: {\n // concat task \"foo\" target options and files go here.\n },\n bar: {\n // concat task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\n },\n },\n uglify: {\n bar: {\n // uglify task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\n },\n },\n});</span></pre>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2.Options</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Inside a task configuration, an options property may be specified to override built-in defaults.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Compact Format</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form allows a single src-dest (source-destination) file mapping per-target. It is most commonly used for read-only tasks, like grunt-contrib-jshint, where a single src property is needed, and no dest key is relevant. This format also supports additional properties per src-dest file mapping.</span></p>\n\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\n jshint: {\n foo: {\n src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\']\n },\n },\n concat: {\n bar: {\n src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\n dest: \'dest/b.js\',\n },\n },\n});</span></pre>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Object Format</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest mappings per-target, where the property name is the destination file, and its value is the source file(s). Any number of src-dest file mappings may be specified in this way, but additional properties may not be specified per mapping.</span></p>\n\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\n concat: {\n foo: {\n files: {\n \'dest/a.js\': [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'],\n \'dest/a1.js\': [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'],\n },\n },\n bar: {\n files: {\n \'dest/b.js\': [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\n \'dest/b1.js\': [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'],\n },\n },\n },\n});</span></pre>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Array Format</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest file mappings per-target, while also allowing additional properties per mapping.</span></p>\n\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\n concat: {\n foo: {\n files: [\n {src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'], dest: \'dest/a.js\'},\n {src: [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'], dest: \'dest/a1.js\'},\n ],\n },\n bar: {\n files: [\n {src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'], dest: \'dest/b/\', nonull: true},\n {src: [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'], dest: \'dest/b1/\', filter: \'isFile\'},\n ],\n },\n },\n});</span></pre>\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Globbing patterns</span></p>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">It is often impractical to specify all source filepaths individually, so Grunt supports filename expansion (also known as globbing) via the built-in node-glob and minimatch libraries.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">While this isn\'t a comprehensive tutorial on globbing patterns, know that in a filepath:</span>\n<ul>\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">* matches any number of characters, but not /</span></li>\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">? matches a single character, but not /</span></li>\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">** matches any number of characters, including /, as long as it\'s the only thing in a path part</span></li>\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">{} allows for a comma-separated list of \"or\" expressions</span></li>\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">! at the beginning of a pattern will negate the match</span></li>\n</ul>\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">All most people need to know is that foo/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory, but foo/**/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory and all of its subdirectories.</span>\n\n&nbsp;','Working with Grunt','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-autosave-v1','','','2016-10-21 16:40:46','2016-10-21 20:40:46','',179,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/179-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(184,1,'2016-10-21 15:51:55','2016-10-21 19:51:55','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Update your system and install latest npm</span>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\" style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install npm</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2. Install Grunt</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudonpm install -g grunt-init</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$grunt-init gruntfile</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Installing Grunt and gruntplugins</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ npm install grunt --save-dev</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$npm install grunt-contrib-jshint --save-dev</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The easiest way to add Grunt and gruntplugins to an existing package.json is with the command npm install &lt;module&gt; --save-dev. Not only will this install &lt;module&gt; locally, but it will automatically be added to the devDependencies section, using a tilde version range.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">5.The Gruntfile</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The Gruntfile.js or Gruntfile.coffee file is a valid JavaScript or CoffeeScript file that belongs in the root directory of your project, next to the package.json file, and should be committed with your project source.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Grunt Configuration</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">1.Task Configuration and Targets</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">When a task is run, Grunt looks for its configuration under a property of the same name. Multi-tasks can have multiple configurations, defined using arbitrarily named \"targets.\" In the example below, the concat task has foo and bar targets, while the uglify task only has a bar target.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n // concat task \"foo\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n // concat task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n uglify: {\r\n bar: {\r\n // uglify task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">2.Options</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Inside a task configuration, an options property may be specified to override built-in defaults.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">3.Compact Format</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">This form allows a single src-dest (source-destination) file mapping per-target. It is most commonly used for read-only tasks, like grunt-contrib-jshint, where a single src property is needed, and no dest key is relevant. This format also supports additional properties per src-dest file mapping.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n jshint: {\r\n foo: {\r\n src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\']\r\n },\r\n },\r\n concat: {\r\n bar: {\r\n src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n dest: \'dest/b.js\',\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Files Object Format</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">This form supports multiple src-dest mappings per-target, where the property name is the destination file, and its value is the source file(s). Any number of src-dest file mappings may be specified in this way, but additional properties may not be specified per mapping.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/a.js\': [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'],\r\n \'dest/a1.js\': [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/b.js\': [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n \'dest/b1.js\': [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Files Array Format</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">This form supports multiple src-dest file mappings per-target, while also allowing additional properties per mapping.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'], dest: \'dest/a.js\'},\r\n {src: [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'], dest: \'dest/a1.js\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'], dest: \'dest/b/\', nonull: true},\r\n {src: [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'], dest: \'dest/b1/\', filter: \'isFile\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">4.Globbing patterns</p>\r\nIt is often impractical to specify all source filepaths individually, so Grunt supports filename expansion (also known as globbing) via the built-in node-glob and minimatch libraries.\r\n\r\nWhile this isn\'t a comprehensive tutorial on globbing patterns, know that in a filepath:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>* matches any number of characters, but not /</li>\r\n 	<li>? matches a single character, but not /</li>\r\n 	<li>** matches any number of characters, including /, as long as it\'s the only thing in a path part</li>\r\n 	<li>{} allows for a comma-separated list of \"or\" expressions</li>\r\n 	<li>! at the beginning of a pattern will negate the match</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAll most people need to know is that foo/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory, but foo/**/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory and all of its subdirectories.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Working with Grunt','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-v1','','','2016-10-21 15:51:55','2016-10-21 19:51:55','',179,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/179-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(185,1,'2016-10-21 15:52:01','2016-10-21 19:52:01','1.Update your system and install latest npm\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo apt-get install npm</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">2. Install Grunt</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$ sudonpm install -g grunt-init</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$grunt-init gruntfile</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">4.Installing Grunt and gruntplugins</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$ npm install grunt --save-dev</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$npm install grunt-contrib-jshint --save-dev</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The easiest way to add Grunt and gruntplugins to an existing package.json is with the command npm install &lt;module&gt; --save-dev. Not only will this install &lt;module&gt; locally, but it will automatically be added to the devDependencies section, using a tilde version range.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">5.The Gruntfile</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">The Gruntfile.js or Gruntfile.coffee file is a valid JavaScript or CoffeeScript file that belongs in the root directory of your project, next to the package.json file, and should be committed with your project source.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Grunt Configuration</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">1.Task Configuration and Targets</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">When a task is run, Grunt looks for its configuration under a property of the same name. Multi-tasks can have multiple configurations, defined using arbitrarily named \"targets.\" In the example below, the concat task has foo and bar targets, while the uglify task only has a bar target.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n // concat task \"foo\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n // concat task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n uglify: {\r\n bar: {\r\n // uglify task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">2.Options</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Inside a task configuration, an options property may be specified to override built-in defaults.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">3.Compact Format</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">This form allows a single src-dest (source-destination) file mapping per-target. It is most commonly used for read-only tasks, like grunt-contrib-jshint, where a single src property is needed, and no dest key is relevant. This format also supports additional properties per src-dest file mapping.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n jshint: {\r\n foo: {\r\n src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\']\r\n },\r\n },\r\n concat: {\r\n bar: {\r\n src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n dest: \'dest/b.js\',\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Files Object Format</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">This form supports multiple src-dest mappings per-target, where the property name is the destination file, and its value is the source file(s). Any number of src-dest file mappings may be specified in this way, but additional properties may not be specified per mapping.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/a.js\': [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'],\r\n \'dest/a1.js\': [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/b.js\': [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n \'dest/b1.js\': [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Files Array Format</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">This form supports multiple src-dest file mappings per-target, while also allowing additional properties per mapping.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'], dest: \'dest/a.js\'},\r\n {src: [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'], dest: \'dest/a1.js\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'], dest: \'dest/b/\', nonull: true},\r\n {src: [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'], dest: \'dest/b1/\', filter: \'isFile\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">4.Globbing patterns</p>\r\nIt is often impractical to specify all source filepaths individually, so Grunt supports filename expansion (also known as globbing) via the built-in node-glob and minimatch libraries.\r\n\r\nWhile this isn\'t a comprehensive tutorial on globbing patterns, know that in a filepath:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>* matches any number of characters, but not /</li>\r\n 	<li>? matches a single character, but not /</li>\r\n 	<li>** matches any number of characters, including /, as long as it\'s the only thing in a path part</li>\r\n 	<li>{} allows for a comma-separated list of \"or\" expressions</li>\r\n 	<li>! at the beginning of a pattern will negate the match</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAll most people need to know is that foo/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory, but foo/**/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory and all of its subdirectories.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Working with Grunt','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-v1','','','2016-10-21 15:52:01','2016-10-21 19:52:01','',179,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/179-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(186,1,'2016-10-21 15:52:29','2016-10-21 19:52:29','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Update your system and install latest npm</span>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\" style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install npm</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2. Install Grunt</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudonpm install -g grunt-init</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</span></p>\r\n\r