 bar: {\r\n src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n dest: \'dest/b.js\',\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Object Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest mappings per-target, where the property name is the destination file, and its value is the source file(s). Any number of src-dest file mappings may be specified in this way, but additional properties may not be specified per mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/a.js\': [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'],\r\n \'dest/a1.js\': [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/b.js\': [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n \'dest/b1.js\': [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Array Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest file mappings per-target, while also allowing additional properties per mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'], dest: \'dest/a.js\'},\r\n {src: [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'], dest: \'dest/a1.js\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'], dest: \'dest/b/\', nonull: true},\r\n {src: [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'], dest: \'dest/b1/\', filter: \'isFile\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Globbing patterns</span></p>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">It is often impractical to specify all source filepaths individually, so Grunt supports filename expansion (also known as globbing) via the built-in node-glob and minimatch libraries.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">While this isn\'t a comprehensive tutorial on globbing patterns, know that in a filepath:</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">* matches any number of characters, but not /</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">? matches a single character, but not /</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">** matches any number of characters, including /, as long as it\'s the only thing in a path part</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">{} allows for a comma-separated list of \"or\" expressions</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">! at the beginning of a pattern will negate the match</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">All most people need to know is that foo/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory, but foo/**/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory and all of its subdirectories.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Working with Grunt','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-v1','','','2016-10-21 15:53:04','2016-10-21 19:53:04','',179,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/179-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(188,1,'2016-10-21 16:11:07','2016-10-21 20:11:07','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Update your system and install latest npm</span>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\" style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install npm</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2. Install Grunt</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudonpm install -g grunt-init</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$grunt-init gruntfile</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Installing Grunt and gruntplugins</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ npm install grunt --save-dev</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$npm install grunt-contrib-jshint --save-dev</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The easiest way to add Grunt and gruntplugins to an existing package.json is with the command npm install &lt;module&gt; --save-dev. Not only will this install &lt;module&gt; locally, but it will automatically be added to the devDependencies section, using a tilde version range.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">5.The Gruntfile</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The Gruntfile.js or Gruntfile.coffee file is a valid JavaScript or CoffeeScript file that belongs in the root directory of your project, next to the package.json file, and should be committed with your project source.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">6.Running Grunt</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">You can find your project plugin in here:http://gruntjs.com/plugins, if you open your Gruntfile.js, you seea task like this:<strong>grunt.registerTask(\'default\', [\'jshint\', \'concat\', \'sass\']);</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">Then you can running your project by:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\">$ grunt default --force</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<h1 class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Grunt Configuration</span></h1>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Task Configuration and Targets</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">When a task is run, Grunt looks for its configuration under a property of the same name. Multi-tasks can have multiple configurations, defined using arbitrarily named \"targets.\" In the example below, the concat task has foo and bar targets, while the uglify task only has a bar target.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n // concat task \"foo\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n // concat task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n uglify: {\r\n bar: {\r\n // uglify task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2.Options</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Inside a task configuration, an options property may be specified to override built-in defaults.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Compact Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form allows a single src-dest (source-destination) file mapping per-target. It is most commonly used for read-only tasks, like grunt-contrib-jshint, where a single src property is needed, and no dest key is relevant. This format also supports additional properties per src-dest file mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n jshint: {\r\n foo: {\r\n src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\']\r\n },\r\n },\r\n concat: {\r\n bar: {\r\n src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n dest: \'dest/b.js\',\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Object Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest mappings per-target, where the property name is the destination file, and its value is the source file(s). Any number of src-dest file mappings may be specified in this way, but additional properties may not be specified per mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/a.js\': [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'],\r\n \'dest/a1.js\': [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/b.js\': [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n \'dest/b1.js\': [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Array Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest file mappings per-target, while also allowing additional properties per mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'], dest: \'dest/a.js\'},\r\n {src: [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'], dest: \'dest/a1.js\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'], dest: \'dest/b/\', nonull: true},\r\n {src: [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'], dest: \'dest/b1/\', filter: \'isFile\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Globbing patterns</span></p>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">It is often impractical to specify all source filepaths individually, so Grunt supports filename expansion (also known as globbing) via the built-in node-glob and minimatch libraries.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">While this isn\'t a comprehensive tutorial on globbing patterns, know that in a filepath:</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">* matches any number of characters, but not /</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">? matches a single character, but not /</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">** matches any number of characters, including /, as long as it\'s the only thing in a path part</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">{} allows for a comma-separated list of \"or\" expressions</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">! at the beginning of a pattern will negate the match</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">All most people need to know is that foo/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory, but foo/**/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory and all of its subdirectories.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Working with Grunt','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-v1','','','2016-10-21 16:11:07','2016-10-21 20:11:07','',179,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/179-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(189,1,'2016-10-21 16:11:23','2016-10-21 20:11:23','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Update your system and install latest npm</span>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\" style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install npm</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2. Install Grunt</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudonpm install -g grunt-init</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$grunt-init gruntfile</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Installing Grunt and gruntplugins</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ npm install grunt --save-dev</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$npm install grunt-contrib-jshint --save-dev</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The easiest way to add Grunt and gruntplugins to an existing package.json is with the command npm install &lt;module&gt; --save-dev. Not only will this install &lt;module&gt; locally, but it will automatically be added to the devDependencies section, using a tilde version range.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">5.The Gruntfile</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The Gruntfile.js or Gruntfile.coffee file is a valid JavaScript or CoffeeScript file that belongs in the root directory of your project, next to the package.json file, and should be committed with your project source.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">6.Running Grunt</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">You can find your project plugin in here:http://gruntjs.com/plugins, if you open your Gruntfile.js, you seea task like this:<strong>grunt.registerTask(\'default\', [\'jshint\', \'concat\', \'sass\']);</strong></span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Then you can running your project by:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ grunt default --force</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<h1 class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Grunt Configuration</span></h1>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Task Configuration and Targets</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">When a task is run, Grunt looks for its configuration under a property of the same name. Multi-tasks can have multiple configurations, defined using arbitrarily named \"targets.\" In the example below, the concat task has foo and bar targets, while the uglify task only has a bar target.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n // concat task \"foo\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n // concat task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n uglify: {\r\n bar: {\r\n // uglify task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2.Options</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Inside a task configuration, an options property may be specified to override built-in defaults.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Compact Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form allows a single src-dest (source-destination) file mapping per-target. It is most commonly used for read-only tasks, like grunt-contrib-jshint, where a single src property is needed, and no dest key is relevant. This format also supports additional properties per src-dest file mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n jshint: {\r\n foo: {\r\n src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\']\r\n },\r\n },\r\n concat: {\r\n bar: {\r\n src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n dest: \'dest/b.js\',\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Object Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest mappings per-target, where the property name is the destination file, and its value is the source file(s). Any number of src-dest file mappings may be specified in this way, but additional properties may not be specified per mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/a.js\': [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'],\r\n \'dest/a1.js\': [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/b.js\': [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n \'dest/b1.js\': [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Array Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest file mappings per-target, while also allowing additional properties per mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'], dest: \'dest/a.js\'},\r\n {src: [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'], dest: \'dest/a1.js\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'], dest: \'dest/b/\', nonull: true},\r\n {src: [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'], dest: \'dest/b1/\', filter: \'isFile\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Globbing patterns</span></p>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">It is often impractical to specify all source filepaths individually, so Grunt supports filename expansion (also known as globbing) via the built-in node-glob and minimatch libraries.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">While this isn\'t a comprehensive tutorial on globbing patterns, know that in a filepath:</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">* matches any number of characters, but not /</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">? matches a single character, but not /</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">** matches any number of characters, including /, as long as it\'s the only thing in a path part</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">{} allows for a comma-separated list of \"or\" expressions</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">! at the beginning of a pattern will negate the match</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">All most people need to know is that foo/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory, but foo/**/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory and all of its subdirectories.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Working with Grunt','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-v1','','','2016-10-21 16:11:23','2016-10-21 20:11:23','',179,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/179-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(190,1,'2016-10-21 16:11:36','2016-10-21 20:11:36','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Update your system and install latest npm</span>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\" style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install npm</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2. Install Grunt</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudonpm install -g grunt-init</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$grunt-init gruntfile</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Installing Grunt and gruntplugins</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ npm install grunt --save-dev</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$npm install grunt-contrib-jshint --save-dev</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The easiest way to add Grunt and gruntplugins to an existing package.json is with the command npm install &lt;module&gt; --save-dev. Not only will this install &lt;module&gt; locally, but it will automatically be added to the devDependencies section, using a tilde version range.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">5.The Gruntfile</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The Gruntfile.js or Gruntfile.coffee file is a valid JavaScript or CoffeeScript file that belongs in the root directory of your project, next to the package.json file, and should be committed with your project source.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">6.Running Grunt</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">You can find your project plugin in here:http://gruntjs.com/plugins, if you open your Gruntfile.js, you seea task like this:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>grunt.registerTask(\'default\', [\'jshint\', \'concat\', \'sass\']);</strong></span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Then you can running your project by:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ grunt default --force</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<h1 class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Grunt Configuration</span></h1>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Task Configuration and Targets</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">When a task is run, Grunt looks for its configuration under a property of the same name. Multi-tasks can have multiple configurations, defined using arbitrarily named \"targets.\" In the example below, the concat task has foo and bar targets, while the uglify task only has a bar target.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n // concat task \"foo\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n // concat task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n uglify: {\r\n bar: {\r\n // uglify task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2.Options</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Inside a task configuration, an options property may be specified to override built-in defaults.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Compact Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form allows a single src-dest (source-destination) file mapping per-target. It is most commonly used for read-only tasks, like grunt-contrib-jshint, where a single src property is needed, and no dest key is relevant. This format also supports additional properties per src-dest file mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n jshint: {\r\n foo: {\r\n src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\']\r\n },\r\n },\r\n concat: {\r\n bar: {\r\n src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n dest: \'dest/b.js\',\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Object Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest mappings per-target, where the property name is the destination file, and its value is the source file(s). Any number of src-dest file mappings may be specified in this way, but additional properties may not be specified per mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/a.js\': [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'],\r\n \'dest/a1.js\': [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/b.js\': [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n \'dest/b1.js\': [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Array Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest file mappings per-target, while also allowing additional properties per mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'], dest: \'dest/a.js\'},\r\n {src: [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'], dest: \'dest/a1.js\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'], dest: \'dest/b/\', nonull: true},\r\n {src: [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'], dest: \'dest/b1/\', filter: \'isFile\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Globbing patterns</span></p>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">It is often impractical to specify all source filepaths individually, so Grunt supports filename expansion (also known as globbing) via the built-in node-glob and minimatch libraries.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">While this isn\'t a comprehensive tutorial on globbing patterns, know that in a filepath:</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">* matches any number of characters, but not /</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">? matches a single character, but not /</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">** matches any number of characters, including /, as long as it\'s the only thing in a path part</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">{} allows for a comma-separated list of \"or\" expressions</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">! at the beginning of a pattern will negate the match</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">All most people need to know is that foo/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory, but foo/**/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory and all of its subdirectories.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Working with Grunt','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-v1','','','2016-10-21 16:11:36','2016-10-21 20:11:36','',179,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/179-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(191,1,'2016-10-21 16:32:45','2016-10-21 20:32:45','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Update your system and install latest npm</span>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\" style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install npm</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2. Install Grunt</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo npm install -g grunt-cli</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudonpm install -g grunt-init</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Preparing a new Grunt project</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$grunt-init gruntfile</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Installing Grunt and gruntplugins</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ npm install grunt --save-dev</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$npm install grunt-contrib-jshint --save-dev</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The easiest way to add Grunt and gruntplugins to an existing package.json is with the command npm install &lt;module&gt; --save-dev. Not only will this install &lt;module&gt; locally, but it will automatically be added to the devDependencies section, using a tilde version range.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">5.The Gruntfile</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The Gruntfile.js or Gruntfile.coffee file is a valid JavaScript or CoffeeScript file that belongs in the root directory of your project, next to the package.json file, and should be committed with your project source.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">6.Running Grunt</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">You can find your project plugin in here:http://gruntjs.com/plugins, if you open your Gruntfile.js, you seea task like this:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>grunt.registerTask(\'default\', [\'jshint\', \'concat\', \'sass\']);</strong></span></blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Then you can running your project by:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ grunt default --force</span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Call watch will keep listen files change then do some tasks</span></p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><strong>grunt.registerTask(\'watch-default\', [\'watch\']);</strong></span></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"></p>\r\n\r\n<h1 class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Grunt Configuration</span></h1>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Task Configuration and Targets</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">When a task is run, Grunt looks for its configuration under a property of the same name. Multi-tasks can have multiple configurations, defined using arbitrarily named \"targets.\" In the example below, the concat task has foo and bar targets, while the uglify task only has a bar target.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n // concat task \"foo\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n // concat task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n uglify: {\r\n bar: {\r\n // uglify task \"bar\" target options and files go here.\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">2.Options</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Inside a task configuration, an options property may be specified to override built-in defaults.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">3.Compact Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form allows a single src-dest (source-destination) file mapping per-target. It is most commonly used for read-only tasks, like grunt-contrib-jshint, where a single src property is needed, and no dest key is relevant. This format also supports additional properties per src-dest file mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n jshint: {\r\n foo: {\r\n src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\']\r\n },\r\n },\r\n concat: {\r\n bar: {\r\n src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n dest: \'dest/b.js\',\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Object Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest mappings per-target, where the property name is the destination file, and its value is the source file(s). Any number of src-dest file mappings may be specified in this way, but additional properties may not be specified per mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/a.js\': [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'],\r\n \'dest/a1.js\': [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: {\r\n \'dest/b.js\': [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'],\r\n \'dest/b1.js\': [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Files Array Format</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">This form supports multiple src-dest file mappings per-target, while also allowing additional properties per mapping.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">grunt.initConfig({\r\n concat: {\r\n foo: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/aa.js\', \'src/aaa.js\'], dest: \'dest/a.js\'},\r\n {src: [\'src/aa1.js\', \'src/aaa1.js\'], dest: \'dest/a1.js\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n bar: {\r\n files: [\r\n {src: [\'src/bb.js\', \'src/bbb.js\'], dest: \'dest/b/\', nonull: true},\r\n {src: [\'src/bb1.js\', \'src/bbb1.js\'], dest: \'dest/b1/\', filter: \'isFile\'},\r\n ],\r\n },\r\n },\r\n});</span></pre>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">4.Globbing patterns</span></p>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">It is often impractical to specify all source filepaths individually, so Grunt supports filename expansion (also known as globbing) via the built-in node-glob and minimatch libraries.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">While this isn\'t a comprehensive tutorial on globbing patterns, know that in a filepath:</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">* matches any number of characters, but not /</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">? matches a single character, but not /</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">** matches any number of characters, including /, as long as it\'s the only thing in a path part</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">{} allows for a comma-separated list of \"or\" expressions</span></li>\r\n 	<li><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">! at the beginning of a pattern will negate the match</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">All most people need to know is that foo/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory, but foo/**/*.js will match all files ending with .js in the foo/ subdirectory and all of its subdirectories.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Working with Grunt','','inherit','closed','closed','','179-revision-v1','','','2016-10-21 16:32:45','2016-10-21 20:32:45','',179,'http://blog.zhexiao.me/179-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(192,1,'2016-10-21 16:33:30','2016-10-21 20:33:30','<span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">1.Update your system and install latest npm</span>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\" style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$ sudo apt-get update</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo apt-get install nodejs</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">$sudo